          <h2>Lesson 1: Introduction to the Internal</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            This week your AS 91604 internal assessment goes live. The task is a written
            report on how a homeostatic system keeps one variable stable in your body.
            You've been preparing for this since Week 7 &mdash; now you put it to work.
          </p>


          <!-- ── Standard Overview ── -->
          <h3>The Standard &mdash; AS 91604 &quot;Keeping it Steady&quot;</h3>

          <p>
            <strong>Achievement Standard Biology 3.4 (91604) V2</strong> &mdash; Demonstrate
            understanding of how an animal maintains a stable internal environment.
            <strong>3 credits, Internal.</strong>
          </p>
          <p>
            You will write a report on the homeostatic processes that regulate a chosen body
            system in relation to a chosen activity or context. You describe the system,
            explain the mechanism, and analyse a disruption. There are four response boxes
            in the assessment document.
          </p>

          <div class="deadline-banner">
            <div class="deadline-banner__left">
              <span class="deadline-banner__label">Deadline</span>
              <span class="deadline-banner__date">Friday 8 May 2026 &bull; 23:59</span>
            </div>
            <div class="deadline-banner__right">
              <span class="deadline-banner__meta">Set as an Assignment in Teams</span>
              <span class="deadline-banner__meta">BIO3 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── The Four Parts ── -->
          <h3>The Four Parts of the Report</h3>

          <p>
            Each part of the report targets a specific grade. Parts A, B and C are needed
            for Achieved and Merit. Part D is where Excellence is earned &mdash; you must
            complete a minimum of two of the three options, and your strongest response is
            the one used for grading.
          </p>

          <div class="parts-grid">

            <div class="part-card part-card--a">
              <div class="part-card__header">
                <span class="part-card__letter">A</span>
                <div>
                  <h4>The Control System</h4>
                  <span class="part-card__grade">Achieved</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p><strong>Describe</strong> the purpose and components of your chosen system.</p>
              <ul>
                <li>What the system does and why it is essential for survival</li>
                <li>The set point and normal range for the regulated variable</li>
                <li>Receptor(s) that detect changes from the set point</li>
                <li>Control centre that processes the signal</li>
                <li>Effector(s) that carry out the corrective response</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="part-card__note">
                Note: Part A alone is not enough for Achieved. The report must also show how
                balance is re-established (that is Parts B and C).
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="part-card part-card--b">
              <div class="part-card__header">
                <span class="part-card__letter">B</span>
                <div>
                  <h4>The Mechanism</h4>
                  <span class="part-card__grade">Merit</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p><strong>Explain</strong> how the components work together via negative feedback.</p>
              <ul>
                <li>How the system detects and responds to normal fluctuations</li>
                <li>How <em>and why</em> each component responds</li>
                <li>How the negative feedback loop returns the variable to the set point</li>
                <li>Interaction and communication between components</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="part-card__note">
                Cover <strong>both directions</strong> of the loop &mdash; the response to
                both high and low levels of the regulated variable.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="part-card part-card--c">
              <div class="part-card__header">
                <span class="part-card__letter">C</span>
                <div>
                  <h4>Disruption &amp; Recovery</h4>
                  <span class="part-card__grade">Merit</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>Choose <strong>one specific extreme disruption</strong> and explain how the body responds.</p>
              <ul>
                <li>What the disruption is and how it affects the system</li>
                <li>What happens as the variable moves outside the normal range</li>
                <li>How the homeostatic mechanisms re-establish balance</li>
                <li>How the system returns to its set point</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="part-card__note">
                Examples: exercise, moderate dehydration, infection, mild poisoning, or a
                genetic variation that reduces (but does not eliminate) the system's
                effectiveness. Stay focused on the biology, not the scenario.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="part-card part-card--d">
              <div class="part-card__header">
                <span class="part-card__letter">D</span>
                <div>
                  <h4>Going Deeper</h4>
                  <span class="part-card__grade">Excellence</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>Answer <strong>at least two</strong> of the three options below. The strongest is used for grading.</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Adaptive advantage:</strong> why natural selection favoured this mechanism; the survival consequences of its failure</li>
                <li><strong>Biochemical / biophysical processes:</strong> equilibrium reactions, membrane permeability, metabolic pathways, signal transduction</li>
                <li><strong>Extreme environmental breakdown:</strong> analyse a specific example of how extreme conditions overwhelm the system &mdash; name the receptors, pathways, or effectors that fail, and why</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="part-card__note">
                Excellence requires you to <strong>link biological ideas back to your specific
                system</strong>. Generic statements about natural selection or biochemistry
                will not cut it.
              </p>
            </div>

          </div>


